<HEADLINE>
VATICAN UNIVERSITY REPRESENTATIVES VISIT TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  8 (CNA) 01/08/07  21:40:16 (By Y.L.Kao)
</P>
<P>
Gianfranco Ghirlanda, president of the Vatican's Pontifical
Gregorian University, and Mario Farrugia, a professor at the
university in charge of interscholastic affairs, international
cooperation and academic exchanges, arrived in Taipei Monday for
a six-day visit, a Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA) official
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, they will visit major Catholic
Universities  and academic  institutions  in Taiwan to promote
interschool exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The representatives will call on Kuo Wei-hsia, mission vice
president of Fun Jen Catholic University, Providence University
President Yu Min-teh, and Wenzao Ursuline College President Lee
Wen-ruey, and deliver speeches on campus, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
The official said during the visit they will also call on several
Catholic clergymembers, including His Eminence Paul Cardinal Shan
Kuo-hsi, Archbishop Joseph Cheng Tsai-fa, Bishop Wang Yu-jung of
Taichung, Bishop Liu Chen-chung of Kaohsiung and Chou Wen-yi,
president of the Kuangchi Program Service.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the Pontifical Gregorian University
was founded by St. Ignatius Loyola, also founder of the Jesuits,
in 1551. It was called the Roman College and later expanded by
Pope Gregorian XIIII and given its current name in 1873.
</P>
<P>
The university has 3,000-plus students, specializes in training
Catholic clergy and serves as a center for learning for theology
scholars.
</P>
<P>
President Ghirlanda has a doctorate in Law and has served as an
Appeals Court judge in Vatican City and as a legal consultant for
related agencies in the Holy See.
</P>
